'''Howard Henry Tooth''', CMG, CB (1856–1925) was a [[Great Britain|British]] [[neurologist]] and one of the discoverers of [[Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease]].

==Early life and education==

Dr Tooth was born on 22 April 1856 to Frederick Tooth of Hove, Sussex, England. He attended [[Rugby School]] and from there attended St John's College in Cambridge. In 1877, he graduated Bachelor of Arts and achieved Master of Arts in 1881.<ref>{{Venn|id=TT873HH|name=Tooth, Howard Henry}}</ref>

After his university education, Howard Henry Tooth studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital, achieving his MD in 1885.<ref name="BMJ 1925">[http://bmj.com/cgi/content/long/1/3360/988-d ''The British Medical Journal'' May 23 1925]</ref>

==Career==

He became Physician to the [[London Metropolitan Hospital]] in 1887. He was also appointed Assistant Physician in the same year at the [[National Hospital for the Paralysed and Epileptic]] and promoted to full Physician in 1907. He was also an assistant Physician at [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]] in 1895 and full Physician in 1906.<ref>http://www.springerlink.com/content/7akl1wylm7p0e5p9</ref>

In 1894 taught a post-graduate course on Cranial Nerves at the National Hospital for the Paralysed and Epileptic.<ref name="BMJ 1894">[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2404897/pdf/brmedj08951-0048d.pdf ''The British Medical Journal'' May 12 1894]</ref>

He was awarded [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] in 1901 and [[Order of the Bath|CB]] in 1918.

==Life in Wartime==

Dr Tooth spent quite a period of time in the military, resulting in him being awarded the rank of [[Colonel]]. During the [[Boer War]], Dr Tooth was stationed in [[South Africa]].<ref name="Journal of Neurology Volume 247 Issue 1">{{cite journal |author=J. M. S. Pearce |year=2000 |title=Howard Henry Tooth (1856-1925) |journal=Journal of Neurology |volume=247 |issue=1 |doi=10.1007/s004150050002 |pages=3–4 |pmid=10701890}}</ref>

Over the period of [[World War I]] he spent time both in London and as a consulting physician to the troops in [[Malta]] and consultant to the British forces in Italy. His services during this time resulted in his name being twice mentioned in the dispatches.<ref name="BMJ 1925"/>

==Civic Participation==
Howard Henry Tooth was a member of the [[Pathological Society of London]]. In 1894, he served as a council member to that society.

==Personality and Personal Life==

Dr Tooth's first marriage was to Mary Beatrice Price, by whom he had one daughter. With his second wife, Helen Katherine Chilver, he had two sons and one daughter.<ref name="Journal of Neurology Volume 247 Issue 1"/>

He died at home in Hadleigh, Suffolk after a cerebral hemorrhage.

==Published Articles==

In 1889 he delivered the [[Goulstonian Lecture]] to the [[Royal College of Physicians]] on the subject of ''Secondary Degeneration of the Spinal Cord''.

